@@eAkh'enet: City of the Eclipsed Ledger@@N

Between the Southern Oasis and the pyramid approach roads stand the broken
walls of @@yAkh'enet@@N -- the legal-mortuary relay that bound oasis water law
to pyramid funerary authority. Caravans, bodies, debt, relics, and verdicts
all moved through this city on their way to deeper desert powers. Its oldest
creed survives in scratched stone: @@d"What is unrecorded becomes famine."@@N

@@rThe Bellwind Collapse@@N

Tremor chains ruptured deep regulator shafts. Aquifer backflow carried brine
into civic cisterns. Resonance bells sounded without human hands. Archive
vaults flooded. The priestly courts called it judgment and doubled down on
descent rites. The Wardens demanded secular control. Akh'enet did not die;
it thinned, each district preserving a different political era in ruin.

@@gSurviving Factions@@N

The @@gReed Ledger Wardens@@N maintain surviving gauges and witness-lamps: water
first, records second, ritual never above either. The @@dMoon Sepulchrists@@N
preserve descent rites; their militant wing seeks to reopen the Nadir
Palace. The @@rSalt Jackal Reclaimers@@N broker relics and forged seals across
desert markets. The @@yCaravan Freeholds@@N keep trade alive through neutral
hostels, remembering who can be paid and where water still rises.

@@lThe Districts@@N

The @@ySunbreak March@@N misdirects newcomers with bleached markers. The
@@gKeeper Roadworks@@N preserve pre-dynastic precision. The @@dShuttered Bazaar@@N
is a contested gray market. The @@lCistern Veins@@N echo with broken pressure
logic. The @@rNecropolis Terraces@@N carve judges as ferrymen and accountants
as priests. The @@eNadir Palace@@N was built to reconcile court, water, and
death in one ceremonial machine -- its failure is Akh'enet's central myth.

@@eWater, Death, and Silence@@N

@@eWater is testimony@@N: every cistern draw is a legal claim. @@dDeath is
administrative continuity@@N: contracts and debt survive the person, and tombs
include filing niches beside iconography. @@rSilence is juridical technology@@N:
moon-influenced courts clarified testimony through acoustic deprivation,
and a verdict issued from silence carried unmatched legitimacy.
